          <h2 class="fw-bold w-100 text-center sub-header">How to Provide Feedback on Drafts Without Overwhelming Designers</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="col">
          <p class="w-100 lead">
            Giving feedback on a website draft should feel like a collaboration, not a frustrating guessing game. Many business owners struggle with vague comments like “Make it pop more” or “It doesn’t feel right,” which can lead to unnecessary revisions and confusion.
          </p>
          <p class="w-100 lead">
            Designers work best when they receive structured and actionable feedback. A clear approach ensures your vision is understood and implemented effectively while keeping the project on track. Here’s how to provide feedback that improves results without overwhelming your design team.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    
      <div class="container">
        <div class="row flex-column px-5">
          <div class="col">
            <h3 class="fw-bold text-secondary mt-4">1. Start with the Big Picture</h3>
            <p class="w-100 lead">
              Before pointing out small details, step back and evaluate the overall design. Does the layout make sense? Is the user experience smooth? Does the website align with your branding? Identifying broad issues first helps ensure the foundation is right before refining smaller elements.
            </p>
            <p class="w-100 lead">
              Consider how a visitor would experience the site. A great design isn’t just about aesthetics—it should communicate your message clearly and guide users toward the intended action. If the website’s purpose is unclear, it may need structural adjustments before focusing on visual details.
            </p>
          </div>
    
          <div class="col">
            <h3 class="fw-bold text-secondary mt-4">2. Be Clear and Specific</h3>
            <p class="w-100 lead">
              Designers can’t act on vague statements like “Make it look better” or “It’s too plain.” Instead, describe what’s not working and why. If a section feels cluttered, mention that you’d prefer more spacing. If a font seems off, explain whether it’s too formal, too playful, or difficult to read.
            </p>
            <p class="w-100 lead">
              Instead of saying, “Change the colors,” specify what’s wrong: “The colors feel too muted. Can we use a brighter shade that matches our brand palette?” This makes it easier for designers to propose effective solutions while maintaining creative freedom.
            </p>
          </div>
    
          <div class="col">
            <h3 class="fw-bold text-secondary mt-4">3. Organize and Prioritize Your Feedback</h3>
            <p class="w-100 lead">
              Avoid overwhelming designers with long, unstructured lists of feedback. Organize your requests into categories based on priority:
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li><p>Major changes: Layout, structure, branding alignment</p></li>
              <li><p>Medium changes: Colors, fonts, images</p></li>
              <li><p>Minor tweaks: Button styles, spacing, text adjustments</p></li>
            </ul>
            <p class="w-100 lead">
              Providing feedback in a structured way helps designers focus on what matters most first, preventing unnecessary back-and-forth.
            </p>
          </div>
    
          <div class="col">
            <h3 class="fw-bold text-secondary mt-4">4. Keep Revisions Efficient</h3>
            <p class="w-100 lead">
              While it’s natural to tweak details, excessive revisions can delay the project. Limit revision rounds by consolidating your feedback and ensuring all decision-makers review drafts before sending comments.
            </p>
            <p class="w-100 lead">
              If you’re part of a team, collect input from all stakeholders before submitting feedback. Conflicting directions slow the process and make it harder for designers to move forward efficiently.
            </p>
          </div>
    
          <div class="col">
            <h3 class="fw-bold text-secondary mt-4">5. Use Visual References</h3>
            <p class="w-100 lead">
              Sometimes words aren’t enough to describe what you want. Use screenshots, links, or design references to illustrate your points. If you prefer a different button style or color scheme, provide examples of what you like.
            </p>
            <p class="w-100 lead">
              Designers often work with mood boards or reference images to understand preferences better. Sharing visual inspiration helps bridge communication gaps and leads to faster, more accurate revisions.
            </p>
          </div>
    
          <div class="col">
            <h3 class="fw-bold text-secondary mt-4">6. Trust Your Designer’s Expertise</h3>
            <p class="w-100 lead">
              While it’s important to communicate your vision, remember that designers bring expertise in user experience, aesthetics, and functionality. If they push back on a request, consider their reasoning before insisting on changes.
            </p>
            <p class="w-100 lead">
              For example, if a designer suggests a different font because the one you chose affects readability, they are likely prioritizing usability. Keeping an open mind ensures your website not only looks great but also performs well.
            </p>
          </div>
    
          <div class="col">
            <h3 class="fw-bold text-secondary mt-4">Final Thoughts: Collaboration Leads to the Best Results</h3>
            <p class="w-100 lead">
              Providing feedback should feel like a conversation, not a list of demands. By keeping it clear, structured, and focused on the big picture, you help designers create a website that meets your goals without unnecessary revisions.
            </p>
